    "title_of_original": "State Aid SA.115160 (2024/NN) - Germany Measures concerning Haitec AG, Flughafen Frankfurt Hahn GmbH, and Ryanair",
    "decided_by": "European Commission",
    "case_description": "Aarhus Midtjylland Airport A/S (“AMA”), a privately-owned operator of Aarhus Midtjylland Airport in eastern Jutland, lodged a formal complaint under EU State aid rules. The complaint concerned an alleged State aid measure granted by the Danish State to Dansk Luftfart A/S ("DL A/S"), a fully state-owned company operating a network of ten airports across Denmark. The measure in question was a capital injection of DKK 2.6 billion (approximately EUR 250 million), carried out on 5 November 2020, following a decision by the Danish Government on 26 October 2020. The capital injection was implemented by the Danish Agency for Public Finance and Management (Statens Administration) pursuant to Danish Law 2020:145 and was financed from the general budget of the Swedish State.
                        On 8 November 2022, Denmark informed the European Commission that it had recovered part of the capital injection from Dansk Luftfart. Specifically, it had recovered DKK 935.2 million, which included DKK 915.8 million of the principal and DKK 19.4 million in interest. Denmark explained that it considered DKK 1,664.8 million of the original DKK 2.6 billion injection to constitute lawful damage compensation aid under Article 107(2)(b) TFEU, granted to offset losses Dansk Luftfart had suffered due to COVID-19-related travel restrictions between 14 March and 30 June 2020 (the "first compensation period") and between 1 July 2020 and 30 June 2021 (the "second compensation period"). These restrictions had significantly affected air traffic, including routes operated or planned to be operated at Dansk Luftfart’s airports.
                        On 20 November 2024, Denmark notified the Commission of an additional recovery of DKK 211.5 million (plus interest). After this recovery, the remaining amount of the capital injection stood at DKK 1,453.3 million." ,
